    <introduction>
      <!-- Uncomment this to generate an outline of the section and sub-section
           titles.  Specify a numeric value as the inner text to limit it to
           a specific number of sub-topics when creating the outline.  Specify
           zero (0) to limit it to top-level sections only.  -->
      <!-- <autoOutline /> -->
		<para>The purpose of this documentation is to provide a thorough overview of the Ukadc.Diagnostics assembly.
		If you just want to get on with using it see the section of quick start guides.</para>
		<para>First off though a bit of history. The .NET framework has been around in one form or another since late 2000, when it was released as a preview
		at the PDC. Version 1.0 was released to manufacture (otherwise known as RTM) on 5th January 2002. At that time the System.Diagnostics namespace
		contained a very rudimentary set of classes - not really up to enterprise scale logging. Since then Microsoft have released multiple updates to the 
		.NET framework and we're currently in the beta phase of .NET 4.0. Along the way a load of interesting features have been added to the framework, and
		most notably for this project, the System.Diagnostics namespace was beefed up a lot in .NET 2.0 to the point where it's now far from rudimentary and
		instead can be used as your only logging/tracing mechanism.</para>
		<para>Since .NET 3.0 Microsoft have also been using the facilities available within the System.Diagnostics namespace to add in logging/tracing 
		functionality to areas of the .NET Framework, so that you can get a diagnostic trace from subsystems such as WCF, WPF and WF. What's good for the goose
		is good for the gander, so you might as well know how this stuff works so that you can utilise it in your own applications too.
		</para>
    </introduction>
